                  <name key="Quintus" type="praenomen">
                     <expan><abbr>Q</abbr><ex>uintus</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name key="Marcius" type="gentilicium">Marcius</name>
                  <lb n="5"/>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Amaranthus">Amaranthus</name>
               </persName>
               <lb n="5"/>coniugi <expan><abbr>b</abbr><ex>ene</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>m</abbr><ex>erenti</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>f</abbr><ex>ecit</ex></expan>.
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the divine spirits. Quintus Marcius Amaranthus made (this) to his wife, Iulia Paepusa, well deserving.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The Latin inscription was copied from a Roman funerary plaque and added to this chest
                    during the 17th century. As such it bears witness to the growing awareness of
                    and interest in epigraphy among scholars and collectors in Renaissance Italy
                    (MMA). The first line is written on the upper frame of the tabula ansata.</p>
         </div>
